S → NT6 NT34.  
NT34 can produce only one of the terminals t3, t41, or t50.  
Therefore, in any string generated from S, the very last token must be t3, t41, or t50.

The given string ends with t54, which NT34 can never produce.

Hence the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

The start symbol expands as S → NT6 NT34.

Because every derivation preserves the left-to-right order of leaves, the substring produced by NT34 must be the final part of the string.  
NT34 can produce only one of the three terminals {t3, t41, t50}.  

The last token of the given string is t52, which is not in {t3, t41, t50}.  
Hence no derivation can match the final token, so the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.
